%N A396184 Irregular triangle read by rows: row 0 is 0, row n for n >= 1 is 6*n^2-3*n+k for k = 1..6*n.
%C A396184 Walk along the hexagonal spiral (as in A395362), with its cells numbered starting at 0. Begin with no kings (the kings are Glinski kings, as in Glinski hexagonal chess). If the square you are at is not attacked by an existing king, place a king there, otherwise leave it empty. The sequence lists the indices divided by 2 of the squares occupied by the kings.
%C A396184 A Glinski king at cell 0 can move to any of 12 cells: 1,2,3,4,5,6, or 7,9,11,13,15,17. The first king is placed at cell a(0) = 0. The smallest unattacked cell is cell 8, so the next king is placed at cell a(1) = 8/2 = 4.
%C A396184 If we ignore the spiral structure the cells themselves form a copy of the A_2 hexagonal lattice, and the cells containing the kings form a sublattice of index 4.
%H A396184 N. J. A. Sloane, <a href="/A396184/a396184.jpg">Sketch showing first 62 cells of the spiral. Black circles indicate the kings, X's indicate cells attacked by earlier kings.</a>
%e A396184 Triangle begins:
